Interestingly, we found the reverse (that abortion is considered a medical need, with little social stigma) in Gilgil, Kenya. Perhaps the most shocking facts to come out about the Situation Room came from Batangal - The Philippines, where we were told that women almost always resort to self-intervention rather than contacting doctors - a fact that underlines how crucial it is that health services be considered to be easily accessible in an appropriate setting. Of course, there are many other viewpoints on the subject, and the interview we conducted painted a diverse canvas of opinions from this situation room. Many complex issues are brought up, and not all aspects were addressed adequately by the languages at our disposal. Co-occurring sentiments include that abortion is a basic human right and should be a legal option, even in narrow circumstances. Furthermore, those speaking from communities where the medical infrastructure is lacking, pointed out the value in ensuring women (and men) have access to and information regarding alternative methods of contraception. In Syrian Kurdistan, this is still a much discussed issue, as people are hesitant to talk about it due to the long term stigma. Laws for abortion can vary within and between nations: In Bangladesh it is illegal in Bangladesh, but in Dubai, UAE, it is legal if requested by the woman within the first 90 days of her pregnancy. Finally, but not least, it is clear that political and social values pertaining to this widespread issue vary
